First, drawing a single number between 20 and 40, and using if() to let me know if the values is \(\geq 25\).

set.seed(6174)
rando <- runif(n = 1, min = 20, max = 40)

2.2. Keeping a counter and performing an operation (cummulative summation).

counter <- 0
sum.counter <- 0
for (i in 1:40) {
  counter <- counter + 1
  sum.counter <- sum.counter + counter
}
message(paste0("The value of the counter is "), counter)
## The value of the counter is 40
message(paste0("The cummulative summation of the counter values is "), sum.counter)
## The cummulative summation of the counter values is 820

2.3. Density-indepedent growth

n.steps <- 10
N.vec <- rep(x = NA, times = n.steps)
lambda <- 1.01
N.init <- 0.01
N.vec[1] <- N.init

for (i in 2:n.steps) {
  N.vec[i] <- lambda*N.vec[i-1]
}

plot(x = 1:n.steps, y = N.vec, xlab = "Step (time)", ylab = "Density")

2.5. When does 2.4 reach 1 or less?

n.steps <- 600
N.vec <- rep(x = NA, times = n.steps)
lambda <- 0.99
N.init <- 100
N.vec[1] <- N.init

for (i in 2:n.steps) {
  if (N.vec[i-1] > 1) {
   N.vec[i] <- lambda*N.vec[i-1] 
  } else {
   break
  }
}

plot(x = 1:n.steps, y = N.vec, xlab = "Step (time)", ylab = "Density")

It took 600 steps. (To write the previous statment, you can type It took r length(N.vec), but replaces each double quote with a backtick.)

2.6.

n.steps <- 20
N.vec <- rep(x = NA, times = n.steps)
r <- 0.99
b <- 0.1
N.init <- 1
N.vec[1] <- N.init

for (i in 2:n.steps) {
   N.vec[i] <- N.vec[i-1]*exp(r*(1 - b*N.vec[i-1]))
}

plot(x = 1:n.steps, y = N.vec, xlab = "Step (time)", ylab = "Density")

The final density is 10!

2.7.

n.steps <- 20
n.rs <- 10
r.vals <- seq(from = 0.1, to = 2, length.out = n.rs)
N.mat <- matrix(data = NA, nrow = n.rs, ncol = n.steps)
b <- 0.1
N.init <- 1
N.mat[, 1] <- N.init

for (i in 1:n.rs) {
  for (j in 2:n.steps) {
    r <- r.vals[i]
    N.mat[i, j] <- N.mat[i, j-1]*exp(r*(1 - b*N.mat[i, j-1]))
  }
}

plot(x = NA, type = "n", xlab = "Step (time)", ylab = "Density", xlim = c(0, n.steps), ylim = c(0, max(N.mat)))
for (k in 1:n.rs) {
  lines(x = 1:n.steps, y = N.mat[k, ], col = rainbow(n = n.rs)[k], lwd = 1.5)
}

3. (Optional challenge) Nested looping with for()

3.1. The lone, optional question in this section asks you to write a nested loop. These come in handy when you want to look at multiple parameters in an ecological model. For the Ricker eqn. in 2.6 we looked at 1 value of \(r\) and 1 value of \(b\) to find the population density after 20 timesteps. In 2.7 we looked at 1 value of \(b\) and 10 values of \(r\) to find the density after 20 time steps. But what if we are interested in the Ricker equation across 10 values of \(r\) and 10 values of \(b\)? These nested loops will do this for you. Please construct a nested for loop to analyze 10 values of \(r\) between 0.1 and 0.5 and 10 values of \(b\) between 0.1 and 1.0. (seq(from = x, to = y, length.out = 45) will, for instance, generate 45 values within the interval of x and y.)

n.steps <- 20
n.rs <- 10
n.bs <- 10
r.vals <- seq(from = 0.1, to = 0.5, length.out = n.rs)
b.vals <- seq(from = 0.1, to = 1.0, length.out = n.bs)
N.arr <- array(data = NA, dim = c(n.rs, n.bs, n.steps))
b <- 0.1
N.init <- 1
N.arr[, , 1] <- N.init

for (i in 1:n.rs) {
  for (j in 1:n.bs) {
    for (k in 2:n.steps) {
      r <- r.vals[i]
      b <- b.vals[j]
      N.arr[i, j, k] <- N.arr[i, j, k-1]*exp(r*(1 - b*N.arr[i, j, k-1]))
    }
  }
}

par(mfrow = c(4, 5), mar = c(3, 3, 0.5, 0.5), oma = c(2, 2, 2, 2)) # mar just sets the whitespace around each panel
for (m in 1:n.steps) {
  image(x = r.vals, y = b.vals, z = N.arr[,,m], las = 1, xlab = "", ylab = "")
  mtext(side = 3, text = paste0("Time step", m), cex = 0.75)
}
mtext(outer = T, side = 1, text = "r values")
mtext(outer = T, side = 2, text = "b values")
